    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-05-07T19:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-05-07T19:00:00-05:00" n="649"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d649">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">611.2331/324a: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Peru</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Norweb</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-05-07T20:00:00-04:00"
                            >May 7, 1942—8 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>398. Trade agreement signed at noon today, including 50 percent reductions in
                    duty on long-staple cotton and sugar. In a separate exchange of notes it is
                    agreed that the Tariff Commission will be requested to investigate possibility
                    of consolidating present individual country quotas on long-staple cotton into a
                    global quota equal to the sum of the individual quotas, thus permitting Peru to
                    share in supplying any otherwise unfilled portions of permitted imports. Upon a
                    favorable finding by the Tariff Commission, the President would then issue a
                    proclamation in the above sense.</p>
                <p>Dasso signed for Peru. Copy of text by air mail.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
                <postscript>
                    <p>[For text of trade agreement, see Department of State Executive Agreement
                        Series No. 256, or 56 Stat. (pt. 2) 1509. For analysis of text of agreement,
                        see Department of State <hi rend="italic">Bulletin</hi>, May 9, 1942, page
                        410.]</p>
                </postscript>
            </div>
